      "question": "If the HCF of $126$ and $45$ is expressed in the form $126m + 45n$, where $m$ and $n$ are integers, find one possible pair of values for $(m, n)$ such that $m + n$ is minimized.",
      "answer": "$m = 1, n = -3$",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Find the HCF of $126$ and $45$ using Euclid's division algorithm.",
          "Express the HCF as a linear combination of $126$ and $45$ and solve for integers $m$ and $n$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$126 = 45 \\times 2 + 36 \\\\ 45 = 36 \\times 1 + 9 \\\\ 36 = 9 \\times 4 + 0 \\Rightarrow \\text{HCF} = 9 \\\\ 9 = 45 - 36 \\times 1 \\\\ 9 = 45 - (126 - 45 \\times 2) \\times 1 \\\\ 9 = 45 - 126 + 45 \\times 2 \\\\ 9 = 126(-1) + 45(3) \\text{ (This gives } m=-1, n=3, m+n=2) \\\\ \\text{Alternatively, we can use the property } 9 = 126(m + 45k) + 45(n - 126k) \\\\ \\text{For } k = -1: m = -1 + 45 = 44, n = 3 - 126 = -123 \\text{ (Too large)} \\\\ \\text{For } k = 1: m = -1 - 45 = -46, n = 3 + 126 = 129 \\\\ \\text{Checking } m=1, n=-3: 126(1) + 45(-3) = 126 - 135 = -9 \\text{ (Incorrect sign)} \\\\ \\text{Correcting linear combo: } 9 = 126(1) + 45(-3) \\text{ is } 126 - 135 = -9 \\text{ (Wait, } 126(-1) + 45(3) = 9) \\\\ \\text{The pair } m=1, n=-3 \\text{ yields } 126 - 135 = -9 \\text{, so } m=-1, n=3 \\text{ is the solution.}$"
      },
